{"parse":{"title":"Hotel thief","pageid":31556519,"revid":845894856,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>A <b>hotel thief</b> is someone who steals items from the rooms of guests at a hotel.\n</p><p>Several factors may attract a thief to a hotel. Rooms are generally empty for most of the day, with few hiding places for valuable possessions outside of a hotel's safe, which not all guests make use of.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Sandoval_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Sandoval-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Furthermore, it is comparatively easy for a thief to leave a hotel without arousing suspicion, as guests are continually coming and going with luggage.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Sandoval_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Sandoval-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Although hotel room security has improved, with more advanced locks, this has not eradicated hotel theft. A thief can enter a room without needing to pick a lock, for example by pretending to be a guest who has left their key in their room.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Jones_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Jones-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Items can also be taken while a guest is distracted, for example when checking in.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Sandoval_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Sandoval-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>One of the most prolific hotel thieves was <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Ernest_Le_Ford&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Ernest Le Ford (page does not exist)\">Ernest Le Ford</a>, who stole thousands of dollars' worth of jewels from hotels in <a href=\"/wiki/New_York_City\" title=\"New York City\">New York City</a> in the early part of the twentieth century, including taking $8000 worth from a room at the <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Manhattan_Square_Hotel&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Manhattan Square Hotel (page does not exist)\">Manhattan Square Hotel</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> Another nineteenth-century hotel thief successfully stole $60,000 worth of gold dust from a San Francisco hotel.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Sandoval_1-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Sandoval-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Hotel_thief&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Sandoval-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Sandoval_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Sandoval_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Sandoval_1-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Sandoval_1-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Sandoval-Strausz, A. K. (2007). <i>Hotel: An American History</i>. <a href=\"/wiki/Yale_University_Press\" title=\"Yale University Press\">Yale University Press</a>. pp.&#160;213\u2013215.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Hotel%3A+An+American+History&amp;rft.pages=213-215&amp;rft.pub=Yale+University+Press&amp;rft.date=2007&amp;rft.aulast=Sandoval-Strausz&amp;rft.aufirst=A.+K.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHotel+thief\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Jones-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Jones_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Jones, Thomas J. A. (2007). <i>Professional Management of Housekeeping Operations</i>. John Wiley and Sons. pp.&#160;320\u2013321.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-20